f3a73-2 | 2026-06-08T10:12:01Z | session:f3a730bf-9a3b-4952-b687-c93ade5fd7ec | **Seam 3 — Adapters are dumb and fail open.** \n Principle: "if tenex-edge is unhealthy, the host's work proceeds unimpeded." The host integrations (Claude Code hooks today; Codex, an MCP server later) are the *straws* — replaceable distribution, not the asset. They translate host events → board updates and board deltas → host context, and that's all. They carry no identity logic, no fabric logic, and they must never block the editor on the daemon being happy. MCP is worth keeping in mind as the portable adapter substrate so you're not hand-writing a bilateral integration per host. [...] User: why are you coupling `pc` wit this? this should have nothing to do with pc -- pc is just for the context injection, but identity and awareness should be independent of pc -- in fact, once this is live we'll remove the awareness substrate from pc and let tenex-edge drive awareness \n  [...] **The adapters (dumb, fail-open straws — `pc` is just one of them):** \n - `pc` captures host activity → feeds it to the substrate, and renders the substrate's awareness deltas back into Claude Code context. It carries no identity, no board, no fabric logic. \n - Other straws later: Codex, an MCP server, mobile. Interchangeable. [...] - `pc` captures host activity → feeds it to the substrate, and renders the substrate's awareness deltas back into Claude Code context. It carries no identity, no board, no fabric logic.
