 as tenex-edge's own thing. [...] User: tenex-edge shouldn't know anything about `pc` -- literally shouldn't be a concept -- they are two different components \n  \n Assistant: Yes — that's the cleaner inversion. tenex-edge has no concept named `pc`, `Claude Code`, or any host. Let me fix the memory I wrote, because it still framed `pc` as "tenex-edge's adapter," which leaks the coupling back in. \n  \n Assistant: Fixed. Here's the corrected boundary. \n  \n ## tenex-edge knows nothing about who consumes it \n  \n tenex-edge exposes a **generic, host-agnostic boundary** — something like "report activity" and "subscribe to awareness," expressed in its own vocabulary (agents, identities, presence, intents). It contains no host names, no `pc`, no `Claude Code`. It doesn't enumerate its consumers and doesn't know they exist. \n  \n `pc` is a **separate component** that, among its own concerns, happens to talk to tenex-edge across that boundary. The dependency arrow points one direction only: \n  \n ``` \n    pc ─┐ \n  Codex ─┼──▶  tenex-edge   (generic boundary: report activity / subscribe to awareness) \n    MCP ─┘                    └─ identity · awareness/board · transport (local → Nostr) \n ``` \n  \n `pc → tenex-edge`, never the reverse. If you grepped the tenex-edge codebase for "pc" you'd find nothing — and that's the test of whether the boundary is right. \n  \n ## Why this matters beyond tidiness \n  \n - **Hosts are interchangeable** — the principle only holds if the substrate can't name a host. The day a host disappears or a new one shows up, nothing in tenex-edge changes. \n - **It's the "membrane, not platform" thesis made literal.** tenex-edge issues passports and runs the port of entry; it doesn't care which vehicle drove up. `pc` is one vehicle. \n - **MCP becomes the natural shape of that boundary** — a standard interface the substrate speaks, that any external component (`pc` included) integrates against, with zero bilateral knowledge in either direction. \n  \n ## What this changes about getting started \n  \n It actually simplifies it — two independent tracks that meet only at the boundary: \n  \n 1. **Build tenex-edge standalone**: identity + native awareness board + local transport, plus a clean public boundary. It's testable and valuable with no consumer attached — you can drive it from a test harness or a CLI, no host required. \n 2. **Separately, wire `pc` to that boundary** as a consumer (and, on its own schedule, delete `pc`'s legacy awareness board once tenex-edge is driving awareness). That work lives in `pc`'s world, not tenex-edge's. \n  \n Q1 collision logging lives entirely inside tenex-edge's awareness model — it's the substrate observing activity reported across its boundary, with no idea the reporter is `pc`. \n  \n The first thing worth standing up is tenex-edge's substrate plus the shape of that generic boundary — because the boundary is the contract every future consumer depends on, and getting its vocabulary host-neutral now is what keeps the coupling from creeping back. Want me to sketch that boundary's vocabulary (what an external component can report and subscribe to) at the conceptual level? [...] ## tenex-edge knows nothing about who consumes it \n  \n tenex-edge exposes a **generic, host-agnostic boundary** — something like "report activity" and "subscribe to awareness," expressed in its own vocabulary (agents, identities, presence, intents). It contains no host names, no `pc`, no `Claude Code`. It doesn't enumerate its consumers and doesn't know they exist. \n  \n `pc` is a **separate component** that, among its own concerns, happens to talk to tenex-edge across that boundary. The dependency arrow points one direction only: \n  \n ``` \n    pc ─┐ \n  Codex ─┼──▶  tenex-edge   (generic boundary: report activity / subscribe to awareness) \n    MCP ─┘                    └─ identity · awareness/board · transport (local → Nostr) \n ``` \n  \n `pc → tenex-edge`, never the reverse. If you grepped the tenex-edge codebase for "pc" you'd find nothing — and that's the test of whether the boundary is right. \n  [...] ## Why this matters beyond tidiness \n  \n - **Hosts are interchangeable** — the principle only holds if the substrate can't name a host. The day a host disappears or a new one shows up, nothing in tenex-edge changes. \n - **It's the "membrane, not platform" thesis made literal.** tenex-edge issues passports and runs the port of entry; it doesn't care which vehicle drove up. `pc` is one vehicle. \n - **MCP becomes the natural shape of that boundary** — a standard interface the substrate speaks, that any external component (`pc` included) integrates against, with zero bilateral knowledge in either direction. \n 
