162f9-1 | 2026-06-09T09:37:40Z | session:162f9965-82ca-420b-aa24-99faa15cb59a | User: we said this:  the db collision issue, wouldn't a WAL state fix that? or perhaps it'd be better to have a single tenex-edge daemon process that if something runs tenex-edge and doesn't exist we create it and fork it to the background and that single reader/writer interfaces with the database through some type of IPC? \n  \n     Short answer: WAL helps but doesn't fix it; the single-daemon-with-IPC is the actual fix, and it's the architecturally right one for tenex-edge anyway. \n  \n     Why WAL alone won't fix it \n  \n     WAL (PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL) changes the concurrency model from "one writer XOR many readers, whole-file locked" to "many concurrent readers + one writer, readers don't block the writer." That's a real improvement and you should turn it on regardless. But the corruption you hit came from ~16 independent processes each holding their own connection to the same file, and WAL does not give you multi-writer concurrency — it still serializes writers. With many writers you get: \n  \n     - SQLITE_BUSY storms unless every connection sets a generous busy_timeout; writers just queue/fail rather than corrupt. \n     - WAL's correctness depends on all processes being on the same machine with working POSIX shared-memory (the -shm/-wal sidecar files). That's true here (all local), so WAL is viable — but it's also where WAL famously breaks (networked FS, and edge cases around processes that open/close connections rapidly). \n     - It doesn't address the deeper smell: 16 writers means 16 things each believe they own state. WAL makes that less likely to corrupt, not correct. \n  \n     So WAL is a seatbelt, not a redesign. It would likely have prevented this specific corruption, but you'd be one weird crash / killed-mid-checkpoint / stale-shm away from the next one. \n  \n     The single-daemon + IPC option is the right fix \n  \n     This is the better answer, and it lines up with what tenex-edge already is. You essentially already run a per-session engine process; the collision came from many of those (plus CLI invocations) all writing state.db directly. Collapsing to one daemon per machine that solely owns the DB, with every tenex-edge CLI call and every session-engine becoming a thin client over IPC, gives you: \n  \n       - One writer, by construction. No WAL-busy juggling, no corruption window. SQLite is happiest single-process. \n       - A natural home for the things that are already machine-global: the relay connection(s), the allowlist/ACL, peer-session staleness pruning, the inbox. Today each session re-opens all of that. \n       - It directly enables the channels/streaming-mention direction from earlier: the daemon is the long-lived relay subscriber, and wait-for-mention / a future subscribe --json / the channel adapter all just stream from the daemon rather than each touching SQLite. \n  \n  Mechanics that fit your stack: \n       - Spawn-if-absent: first tenex-edge invocation that finds no daemon forks one to the background (double-fork / setsid) bound to a Unix domain socket under $TENEX_EDGE_HOME (e.g. ~/.tenex/edge/daemon.sock). UDS over TCP — no port, filesystem perms gate access, no localhost exposure. \n       - Lockfile + socket to make startup race-safe: flock a daemon.lock, whoever wins binds the socket; losers connect. Handle the stale-socket case (socket file exists but nobody listening → reclaim). \n     - Protocol: JSON-RPC / length-prefixed JSON lines over the UDS. The CLI verbs (who, inbox, send-message, turn-start/end) become RPCs; reads and writes both go through the one owner. \n       - Lifecycle: daemon idle-exits when no sessions are alive (you already track session liveness/heartbeats), so it doesn't linger forever. \n  \n  Tradeoffs to go in with eyes open: you now own a daemon's lifecycle (crash recovery, restart, version-skew when the binary upgrades under a running daemon — the macOS resign/xattr reinstall gotcha you already documented gets more relevant), and a hung daemon stalls every session instead of just one. But those are ordinary daemon concerns, and the corruption risk goes to zero rather than "lowered." \n  \n     Recommendation \n  \n     Do both, staged: turn WAL on now (+ busy_timeout, synchronous=NORMAL) as the cheap immediate stopgap so you're not corrupting while you build the real thing — then move to the single machine-daemon that owns state.db and serves CLI + engines + the relay subscription over a UDS. The daemon is the correct destination because it also collapses the per-session relay connections and becomes the clean seam the channel/streaming-mention adapter consumes. Treat WAL as the bandage and the daemon as the cure, not as alternatives. [...]       - A natural home for the things that are already machine-global: the relay connection(s), the allowlist/ACL, peer-session staleness pruning, the inbox. Today each session re-opens all of that. \n       - It directly enables the channels/streaming-mention direction from earlier: the daemon is the long-lived relay subscriber, and wait-for-mention / a future subscribe --json / the channel adapter all just stream from the daemon rather than each touching SQLite. \n 
