162f9-7 | 2026-06-09T09:37:46Z | session:162f9965-82ca-420b-aa24-99faa15cb59a | ## The load-bearing constraint: it must NOT become a second state.db writer \n  \n This is the design fork that matters most, and it's set by your freshest scar ([[tenex-edge-sqlite-multiwriter-corruption]]). A channel is **another per-session subprocess** — Claude Code spawns it from `.mcp.json`, alongside the engine. If that server opens its own `state.db` writer, you've walked straight back into the ~16-writer corruption you just recovered from. \n  \n So the only safe shape: the channel server is a **thin stream-consumer** of the engine — it spawns a long-lived `tenex-edge subscribe --json` (or `tail`), reads stdout, emits one `notifications/claude/channel` per line, and **never independently writes state.db**. Its `reply` tool shells `tenex-edge send-message`. Zero new writers. \n 
162f9-8 | 2026-06-09T09:38:09Z | session:162f9965-82ca-420b-aa24-99faa15cb59a | This also answers the tempting "make the engine itself the MCP server": **no.** That would hand Claude Code ownership of the engine's lifecycle, break it for Codex/OpenCode, and violate the host-agnostic boundary ([[pc-vs-tenex-edge-boundary]]). The channel is an **adapter that lives outside tenex-edge** (`integrations/claude-code/`, next to the hooks), depending on the substrate — arrow pointing the right way. \n 
162f9-9 | 2026-06-09T09:38:09Z | session:162f9965-82ca-420b-aa24-99faa15cb59a | User: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/channels-reference \n  \n  \n we should be using this for injecting async work (linstead of wait-for-mention hack) [...] ## What the substrate actually needs to grow \n  \n One thing, named generically so it isn't a "channel feed": a **streaming mention subscription** — a long-lived command that emits NDJSON, one mention per line, instead of `wait-for-mention`'s exit-on-first-batch. That same seam is what a future mobile or webhook adapter consumes too. tenex-edge stays ignorant of who's reading it. `wait-for-mention` itself stays as the portable floor. \n  [...] ## Honest rollout cost — this is "next," not "today" \n  \n - **Claude-only.** Codex and OpenCode have no channels; they keep the `wait-for-mention`/poll path. So this is an **upgrade to the Claude adapter**, not a fabric-wide replacement. \n - **Can't live in settings.json.** It needs a launch flag — `--channels` (or `--dangerously-load-development-channels server:tenex-edge` during the research preview, v2.1.80+, Anthropic-auth only, not Bedrock/Vertex). That means a launcher wrapper (you already have the `tenex-codex` pattern) or shell alias, not a settings merge. Today's hook-based path is genuinely zero-config; this trades that for the cold-start win. \n - **Research preview / allowlist.** Custom channels need the dev flag until allowlisted; the protocol may still change. \n  \n **Net:** frame `wait-for-mention` as the portable floor that stays for all harnesses, and the channel as the better Claude-specific ceiling — a thin, write-free stream-consumer adapter, gated on your existing ACL allowlist, that finally makes an idle Claude session reachable. [...] Assistant: Codex result is in — and it **refutes my assertion** for Codex. \n  \n **Codex has a real equivalent: `codex app-server`** — a JSON-RPC 2.0 server (stdio / Unix socket / WebSocket). Sending `turn/start` to an idle (resumed) thread *is* the wake — no human prompt needed. That's functionally what channels does, just over Codex's own protocol instead of the MCP notification plane. MCP server-push into Codex specifically does **not** exist yet (open issues #15299, #17543), so the channels-style "MCP server pushes a notification" pattern has no Codex analog — but the app-server `turn/start` path is arguably *more* powerful. \n  \n One caveat the agent underweighted, and it's the load-bearing one for us: **app-server is a separate headless daemon**, architecturally distinct from the interactive-TUI model your current Codex integration uses (the `tenex-codex` launcher, because hooks don't fire under `codex exec`). To make an injected turn show up in the operator's *visible* terminal you'd need the TUI attached via `codex --remote unix://`. So it's a genuine wake primitive, but adopting it means changing how Codex sessions are launched — not a drop-in. (I'd also want to verify the exact verb names — `turn/start`, `thread/resume`, `--remote` — against the binary before building; the agent says it checked 0.138.0 locally, but those are the load-bearing specifics.) \n 
